1) It&#39;s just to receive parameters without making copy. `const` is just to make them &quot;read-only&quot;, they can not be changed. Also, when you use a const reference, you can bind rvalue arguments to lvalue parameters, then you can also pass literals to your function, for instance.

2) There&#39;s an implicit conversion to int whenever the first parameter is an integer for each pair of the unpacking. If you change the `43` value to  `43.0`, it&#39;s going to work. Also, with C++17, you can discard the `Add` function and use a fold expression : `return (arg_a + ... + arg_list);`.

Possible better solution:

    template &lt;typename... Pack&gt;
    auto Add(const Pack&amp;... arg_list) {
        return (arg_list + ...);
    }

**Answer for question 1**

Because some types are expensive to copy, if you are simply doing a summation , which doesn&#39;t modify the underlying objects, pass by const reference eliminates the cost of copying the objects.

For example, if you pass by value a large `vector`, the whole `vector` would be copied to call the function, while passing a const reference is a lot more faster (**likely** implemented as a pointer copy).
 
----------
**Answer for question 2**

Your problem is that when you calculate `43 + 32.2` the return value is `int`, discarding the decimal parts. This is because `T` in this context is deduced to be the type of literal `43`, which is `int`. Two solutions for your problem:

1. Use `auto` for your return value. (If you are on c++ 14)

```c++
template &lt;typename T&gt;
T Add(const T&amp; arg_a)
{
	return arg_a;
}

template &lt;typename T, typename... Pack&gt;
auto Add(const T&amp; arg_a, const Pack&amp;... arg_list)
{
    return arg_a + Add(arg_list...);
}
```

2. Or if you have c++ 17, simply use [fold expressions][1]

```c++
template &lt;typename... Pack&gt;
auto Add(const Pack&amp;... arg_list)
{
	return (... + arg_list);
}
```
3. If you are on c++ 11, use [std::common_type][2]

```c++
template &lt;typename T&gt;
T Add(const T&amp; arg_a)
{
	return arg_a;
}

template &lt;typename T, typename... Pack&gt;
typename std::common_type&lt;T, Pack...&gt;::type Add(const T&amp; arg_a, const Pack&amp;... arg_list)
{
	return arg_a + Add(arg_list...);
}
```

When `std::common_type` doesn&#39;t work (for example, `Add(&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;, &#39;d&#39;)`), you can still write your own sum type deducer in c++ 11:

```c++
template &lt;typename SumLeftT, typename ... Args&gt;
struct sum_t_impl;

template &lt;typename SumLeftT&gt;
struct sum_t_impl&lt;SumLeftT&gt; {
	using type = SumLeftT;
};

template &lt;typename SumLeftT, typename FirstT, typename ... Rest&gt;
struct sum_t_impl&lt;SumLeftT, FirstT, Rest...&gt; {
	using type = typename sum_t_impl&lt;decltype(std::declval&lt;SumLeftT&gt;() + std::declval&lt;FirstT&gt;()), Rest...&gt;::type;
};

template &lt;typename T, typename ... TArgs&gt;
using sum_t = typename sum_t_impl&lt;T, TArgs...&gt;::type;
```

And replace the return value type `typename std::common_type&lt;T, Pack...&gt;` with `sum_t&lt;T, Pack...&gt;`.

This, for example, works for a pack with `char`s, where `char + char -&gt; int`.

```c++
int main()
{
	auto itLocalSum = Add(&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;, &#39;d&#39;);
	std::cout &lt;&lt; typeid(itLocalSum).name() &lt;&lt; std::endl;
	std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Sum of Add: &quot; &lt;&lt; itLocalSum &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
	return 0;
}
```
Will output: `int` and `394`.

  [1]: https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/fold
  [2]: https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/types/common_type

1. Why *wouldn&#39;t* you pass arguments by reference? For integers it doesn&#39;t matter, but I can just as well `Add(std::string{&quot;QWER&quot;}, std::string{&quot;ASDF&quot;}, std::string{&quot;ZXCV&quot;})` and copying those around can get quite costly.

2. You always return left-hand side type, no matter what. It means that if you have `Add(2, 3.5)`, the result must be `int` and it will be casted to such.

To avoid it, you can deduce returned type:

    template &lt;typename T, typename... Pack&gt;
    auto Add(const T&amp; arg_a, const Pack&amp;... arg_list)
    {
        return arg_a + Add(arg_list...);
    }

Regarding the wrong sum... the problem is that 

    template &lt;typename T, typename... Pack&gt;
    T Add(const T&amp; arg_a, const Pack&amp;... arg_list)
    {
        return arg_a + Add(arg_list...);
    }

return a value of the same type of the first argument (`T`).

So, if `T` is an integer, you loose the floating point parts in the following arguments.

In case 

    Add(2.3, 43, 32.2)

you obtain that, after the `43`, `32.2` become `32`.

To solve this problem... if you can use C++17, you can use template folding and simply write

    template &lt;typename ... Ts&gt;
    auto Add (Ts const &amp; ... as)
     { return (as + ...); }

If you can&#39;t use C++17 but you can use C++14, you can simulate template folding as follows

    template &lt;typename ... Ts&gt;
    auto Add (Ts const &amp; ... as)
     {
       using unused = int[];
    
       typename std::common_type&lt;Ts...&gt;::type ret{};
    
       (void)unused { 0, ((void)(ret += as), 0)... };
    
       return ret;
     }

Observe the use of `std::common_type&lt;Ts...&gt;::type` to get a variable of the the returned type.

If you can use only C++11 (so no `auto` without trailing return type), you have to explicit the return type

    template &lt;typename ... Ts&gt;
    typename std::common_type&lt;Ts...&gt;::type Add (Ts const &amp; ... as)
     { 
       // same body as in C++14
     }

&gt; Why is it used const reference for parameters?

When you intend to invoke it as:

    auto itLocalSum = Add(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

the arguments have to be `const&amp;` or just values. i.e.

    template &lt;typename T&gt;
    T Add(const T&amp; arg_a)
    {
        return arg_a;
    }
    
    template &lt;typename T, typename... Pack&gt;
    T Add(const T&amp; arg_a, const Pack&amp;... arg_list)
    {
        return arg_a + Add(arg_list...);
    }

or

    template &lt;typename T&gt;
    T Add(T arg_a)
    {
        return arg_a;
    }
    
    template &lt;typename T, typename... Pack&gt;
    T Add(T arg_a, Pack... arg_list)
    {
        return arg_a + Add(arg_list...);
    }

For simple types, either is fine. `const&amp;` will be more efficient if `T` is expensive to copy.

&gt; When I use floating numbers with a combination of integers like add(2.3, 43, 32.2) it doesn&#39;t show correct value to me. how can I fix it?

You can use `43.0` instead of `43`.
   
When you use `Add(2.3, 43, 32.2)`, the recursive call `Add(43, 32.2)` returns an `int` and truncates the return value to `75`.

